\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5985306 AA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid411975\charrsid4850714 During the First World War my
 second wife followed the occupation of full responsibility of a Gents Outfitters establishment in Newcastle, (replacing the man being called up for war service 1915 when the conscriptions Act was passed). Her hours were 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. (half day Wed.'s)
 and 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. SAT's getting home often after 11 p.m. all for about 20/- per week. She married her first husband in 1917, has a daughter and son, now both married, and both done war service 1939-1945 as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9769733\charrsid4850714 telegraphist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid411975\charrsid4850714  in the Merchant Navy the girl an O
fficer in the Fire Service, their father died 1933, before the war broke out. Widows in those days were allowed pension 10/- per week with the alternative, was to go out to work to make ends meet in the nineteen thirties. Now we are one big Happy Family.

